  "conclusion": {
    "response": 15,
    "explanation": "The data do not support that having children decreases extramarital affairs. Unadjusted comparisons show higher mean affairs for couples with children (1.67) than without (0.91), with a significant Welch t-test (p=0.004726). After adjustment for age, years married, religiousness, education, occupation, rating, and gender, the children coefficient is small and not significant (coef=-0.143, p=0.684, 95% CI [-0.830, 0.545]). Interpretable models (linear/ridge/lasso, trees, and imodels RuleFit/FIGS/HSTree) also indicate children is not a dominant driver versus marital rating, religiousness, age, and years married."
  }
